Maple Grove  Dec 14- 1856
My dear Mr. Kendall;

         Your good, kind, and affectionate letter, which came to me last evening, has done me a good deal of good.  It was a "Balm" to my wounded heart;  Oh! you do not know how my heart beat with joy, when Mr. Bicknell handed me the letter, & my eye caught the handwriting on the envelope.  I knew it was from my own deerly loved Mr. Kendall, so far away in the distant West; but though my heart joyed, yet my hand was tremulous as it tore open the envelope, for I thought perchance, it might be a letter similar to the one I received a few days previous.  But Oh! I was happily disappointed.  It was a dear good letter, & I have read it over many times, that not a bit of its love should escape my notice.  I have laid it all safely away in my heart; & also, that good long kiss, that played upon my lips for a time, has found a choice place
